05:15.279 --> 05:19.182
was the chairman, as I recall. And this is going 
back some 30 years, you know, almost. And...

05:29.127 --> 05:35.837
Senator Jackson was chairman of the military 
application subcommittee. General Gavin sent me

05:37.780 --> 05:51.520
over and said, we cannot get Radford or the 
president or Wilson to prove off on these

05:37.780 --> 05:51.520
artillery projectiles, 155 and 8-inch. They just 
won't do it. With tactical nuclear weapons. He

05:57.912 --> 05:59.274
said, what can you do? I said, well, let's get it 
done. So I go over and I talk to important members of

06:04.162 --> 06:22.168
the House Armed Services, Senate Armed Services, 
and in a matter of a few days,

06:04.162 --> 06:22.168
we get a request from Senator Jackson to brief him 
on our requirements, and we go. General Gavin and I

06:28.447 --> 06:36.740
and one other nuclear specialist in the operating 
business. And we get that approved over the heads

06:36.760 --> 06:44.292
of the President and the Secretary of Defense and 
the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs. That was a part at

06:46.010 --> 06:54.782
that time of the whole thing of trying to save an 
army and make it viable and capable of defending

06:46.010 --> 06:54.782
this country. Give me another specific. Was the 
airborne part of it another specific? Another one

06:58.507 --> 07:00.710
was helicopters. Another one was tactical 
fighters. Another one was tactical airlift. All

07:08.681 --> 07:09.322
of those.

07:13.368 --> 07:15.190
Better munitions. Which ones did you succeed on, 
and which ones couldn't you get through Congress?

07:27.091 --> 07:28.813
I guess we eventually got them all. Eventually got 
them all. The Colonel's Revolt, then, was a heavy

07:32.517 --> 07:38.562
lobbying effort behind the administration. 
Both. Within the public, within the industry, and

07:40.004 --> 07:44.468
within the Congress. Okay, we talked a little bit 
about Congress. How about industry? What did you

07:51.352 --> 07:52.674
