Iyub Khan, A-Y-U-B-K-H-A-N. He was a general, 
commander-in-chief of the armed forces, later

31:40.848 --> 31:44.574
president. And I got deeply involved in that, his 
becoming president. while I was there. He became

31:52.977 --> 31:55.480
president, yes, I will tell you.

31:58.583 --> 32:11.097
But my mission was one of training about five or six 
divisions of the Pakistani Army and equipping

31:58.583 --> 32:11.097
those with American equipment.

32:14.641 --> 32:18.786
And some of the questions that you encountered 
from General Iyub later President Iyub was how can

32:19.272 --> 32:45.519
you

32:19.272 --> 32:45.519
deny me the use

32:19.272 --> 32:45.519
of your military aid equipment in the Azad Kashmir 
border area where we have a United Nations

32:19.272 --> 32:45.519
ceasefire team between the Indians. How can you 
deny me the use of your aid equipment up there

32:49.782 --> 33:11.875
machine guns rifles mortars tanks trucks and that 
sort of thing while at the same time you give the

32:49.782 --> 33:11.875
Indians 300 million grant aid and they go by 
106-millimeter recoilless rifles from you and

33:13.238 --> 33:23.754
Jaguar fighter planes from the British and bring 
them up here and use them against me.

33:28.862 --> 33:34.631
And said, you've been up there, and I'll point them 
out to you, your U.S. equipment.

33:38.757 --> 33:40.039
I said, General, are you...

33:42.753 --> 33:46.739
I'm a military man and a soldier, as you are.

33:51.806 --> 33:54.590
I said, I can't answer that question. I said, 
that's a question that should be asked by your

33:55.892 --> 34:04.364
prime minister of our president.

34:07.468 --> 34:11.494
He said, they're politicians and they won't ask 
each other questions like that.

34:17.600 --> 34:22.528
And he said, that's what's wrong with, and that's 
what's part of the problem here in this country.

34:26.935 --> 34:45.885
He said, your government gives my government 
wheat, and there's

34:26.935 --> 34:45.885
ship load after ship load of wheat stacked in the 
harbor, rotting in Karachi, and my government

34:26.935 --> 34:45.885
doesn't have sense enough or the capability to get 
the weed out to our tribal people and the villagers

34:46.709 --> 34:54.057
here who have sore bellies because they're not 
getting enough to eat. Yet the weed is rotting down

34:55.578 --> 35:00.523
there.

35:00.543 --> 35:02.666
And he said, why does your government do that? Why 
does your government gloat over what support

35:05.248 --> 35:15.619
you're giving us here beyond our capability to 
even manage? and you deny me in an area where I need

35:17.135 --> 35:24.625
things, military, you've limited me to very 
little. Said, are you, said, we have declared

35:26.427 --> 35:35.019
ourselves as friends of the United States, but are 
you really my friend? We're your friend, but are

35:36.080 --> 35:38.844
you really my friend? Because here's what you're 
doing to us. Those questions are very difficult,

35:43.069 --> 35:45.893
very hard to, to explain and you put your American 
foreign policies, put honest people out at the

35:47.003 --> 36:05.101
colonel and general level in a hell of a position.

36:09.566 --> 36:15.492
So

36:09.566 --> 36:15.492
you get on with

36:18.644 --> 36:23.092
or trying to support your government, or you quit 
and get out. So, I think most of the military feels

36:24.354 --> 36:32.387
that they've got something to contribute. Kind of 
swallow hard and go ahead and do the best they can

36:32.407 --> 36:42.745
under the circumstances.

36:48.817 --> 36:52.221
Did you bring the Pakistani divisions? Did you 
bring them up to par? I brought the Pakistani

36:54.284 --> 37:17.895
divisions up to par except in one area, which is a 
crucial area in that part of the world amongst all

36:54.284 --> 37:17.895
of the peoples in the Middle East, including all 
the Arab nations, including the Iranians,

36:54.284 --> 37:17.895
Pakistanis, most all of the people in that area. of 
the world. And that is that they do not understand

37:21.579 --> 37:46.463
this business of logistics support

37:21.579 --> 37:46.463
and the management of the things that's necessary 
in order to keep a fighting force in being and

37:21.579 --> 37:46.463
sustainable during combat. And that's 
ammunition and this was brought out very clearly

37:48.824 --> 38:18.477
against a war which occurred after I left there 
where in the Brits I mean where in the Indians and

37:48.824 --> 38:18.477
Pakistan went at it

37:48.824 --> 38:18.477
over Kashmir area and Pakistani tank battalions 
were just eating up the Indians driving them back

38:20.785 --> 38:29.836
until they ran out of fuel and ran out of 
ammunition, at which point in time they got out of

38:20.785 --> 38:29.836
their tanks, left them, and walked back. They

38:30.377 --> 38:46.036
cited recorded instances of

38:30.377 --> 38:46.036
that. Those soldiers came out of the villages 
ninety percent of them out of the villages.

38:56.173 --> 39:02.042
We're in, they've been there eighteen years with a 
wooden plow and bullocks.

39:06.088 --> 39:09.013
There's not much logistic support there for that. 
And you don't change people overnight. Okay? Now

39:14.441 --> 39:19.108
tell me about the episode of helping the general 
and your role in that. After I'd been there some

39:19.358 --> 39:27.113
time, well, I hadn't been there very long until I 
gained his confidence and he certainly gained

39:19.358 --> 39:27.113
mine. I thought he was one of the most magnificent 
men I had ever met in my life. Why do you say that?

39:35.229 --> 39:37.133
Well, he was the most balanced man. He was a British 
sand hearse trained officer. He commanded, he was

39:42.089 --> 39:52.925
the first commander of a British battalion during 
World War II in India. Normally British units,

39:53.846 --> 39:59.254
those commands are all Brit officers second in 
command is an Indian, or a Pakistani, or a Gurkha,

39:59.842 --> 40:19.751
or whoever it might be, Ethiopia, an Egyptian, 
something like that, but all those commands,

39:59.842 --> 40:19.751
that's the Brits, they had saved those positions, 
except Iyub, I think, was the first one that really

39:59.842 --> 40:19.751
was a commander of a battalion. And he's just one 
brilliant man, and was commander in chief, and had

40:30.183 --> 40:32.065
a great personality. He loved to shoot, loved to 
hunt, and the hunting was great in the Himalayas,

40:32.946 --> 40:39.292
bird shooting. He

40:41.214 --> 40:49.563
was a good horseman, although he didn't play polo, 
he was a good horseman. He wanted me to play golf

40:50.564 --> 40:53.466
with him, which I did. We'd go shooting together, 
Miss Hollingsworth and Begum Ayoub, who was still

41:01.267 --> 41:06.914
in Perda, but Mrs. Ayoub and Mrs. Hollingsworth. 
And the daughters were very close to Mrs.

41:07.475 --> 41:12.020
Hollingsworth. I went by to visit the daughter and 
the son-in-law. The son-in-law was a Wally of

41:16.266 --> 41:20.671
Swat, the governor of Swat State. And so, we were 
kind of a close family. And Ayoub's son knew He was

41:30.511 --> 41:35.196
in the military and we were very close as a matter of 
fact. He called one day, an aide called one day. We

41:40.322 --> 41:48.110
worked from 7 o'clock in the morning until 12 
o'clock and the temperatures were such that you

41:40.322 --> 41:48.110
stayed in the rest of the day.

41:51.374 --> 41:58.061
I went about other things where you were not 
subject to the stress and the heat. None of the

41:58.081 --> 42:00.163
facilities were air conditioned were they? No, 
none.

42:04.453 --> 42:21.014
I had a call about one o'clock, and it was General 
Ayoub's aide, and he said, General Ayoub would

42:04.453 --> 42:21.014
like to speak to you, and I said, yes sir. He said, 
Holly, he said, I didn't get a chance to see you this

42:22.876 --> 42:29.745
morning, he said. Could I come over now?" And I 
said, yes, sir, General, you please do. I'm here at

42:37.881 --> 42:38.642
home. On the veranda, Miss Hollingsworth and Mrs. 
O'Brien, Captain O'Brien's wife was one of my

42:40.865 --> 42:51.077
ordnance officers out of my team of about 12 
officers.

42:54.080 --> 43:00.508
We're sitting on the veranda and our chocodile who 
was a guard, opened the gate and in came the big

43:00.758 --> 43:23.425
black Cadillac limousine and General Ayoub got 
out and greeted the ladies and myself and I knew he

43:00.758 --> 43:23.425
wanted to see me so I said, well, General Ayoub, 
since I didn't get a chance to see you this morning,

43:24.434 --> 43:33.146
Maybe we could excuse ourselves and present the 
ladies here and go back to one of the drawing rooms,

43:24.434 --> 43:33.146
of which there was three in my quarters. He said, oh 
yes, I'd love to. I'd love to do that. So we go back. I

43:40.637 --> 43:42.099
said, sir, it's two o'clock. Would you like a 
whiskey? He said, yes, I believe I would. So we had a

43:47.026 --> 43:47.967
whiskey. It was scotch with water and no ice. 
British style. So the bear came in, and Ibram was a

43:55.467 --> 44:01.837
bear. He brought in a drink, and he said, well, 
said, Holly, I might as well get on with it. I said,

44:11.993 --> 44:12.594
yes, sir. He said, did you ever think about taking 
over a country?

44:21.688 --> 44:23.230
I said, uh, No, sir, not really, but I said I've 
studied all the principles involved and

44:23.733 --> 44:38.716
it's been applied by other governments and 
throughout a large share of history.

44:45.045 --> 44:49.993
And I know key principles that's involved in 
taking over the country and what you have to do.

44:54.530 --> 45:21.195
He said, well,

44:54.530 --> 45:21.195
my government

44:54.530 --> 45:21.195
is trying to run an advanced state of democracy

44:54.530 --> 45:21.195
in order to satisfy your foreign policy 
requirements so we can get aid for our people.

